english:
  title: Record of Bobeop Temple
  author: Lee Saek
  language: eng
  text: |-
    South of the royal capital, north of White Horse Mountain, stands a great temple—a house once given by the late Queen Consort Yoo, wife of our founding king. The fields and people she bestowed remain even now, though the temple fell into ruin long ago.

    Chief Minister Yoon, Lord of Chiwon, together with the Zen Master Law-Cloud of Seonwon, took a solemn vow to restore it. Work began in the cyclical year of Kyemi and was brought to completion. They resolved: "The Great Scripture Collection cannot remain absent," and brought it from Jiangzhe in the year Muja. To shelter these precious texts, they dismantled their own western hall—this was the year Imjin. When the temple halls were finished and all vessels prepared, all that the voice of the dharma and daily life required was set in place. The dedication ceremony was held in the year Gyesa.

    In the year Sinchuk, they held the middle dedication ceremony. That winter, brigands came and laid waste to everything—the halls, the vessels, the scriptures, the images. Little remained. After the nation reclaimed the capital, they made repairs. The Zen Master of Jokgye was invited as guest abbot—this was the year Gapjin. In the year Eulsa, the lady Yoo passed into stillness. The lord grieved and felt the weight of impermanence, and pressed the workers to complete their task with greater urgency. By the following year the work was done. In the year Jeongmi, they brought the Great Scripture Collection again from Jiangzhe. The next year, all vessels were restored anew, and he said: "This is truly the beginning of our temple made new again." Thus they held the first dedication ceremony in the year Gyeongseul, the middle ceremony in the year Jeongsa. In the year Muo, the Zen Master of Jokgye was invited as chief celebrant. Thus began the Ten Thousand Day Amitabha Assembly.

    The halls—not lavish, not mean—inspire reverence in all who behold them. The lady was born on the fifth day of the third month and passed away on the fourth day of the eighth month, so he turns the scriptures twice yearly, marking these dates. His deeper wish is to mark also the day of his own passing into the realm beyond. Ah, how far-reaching his foresight!

    A thousand bolts of silk were given, the principal kept in perpetuity and the interest alone taken for use. Fields in Bupyeong, Gimpo, Suān, and Dongseong—the ancestral holdings of the lord—and lands in Gimpo and Dongseong, the ancestral holdings of the lady, sustain the temple. The annual needs come from these sources; never has the temple begged at a donor's gate. Truly, his method is flawless. In this world, how many bow and scrape at stranger's doors? Can they not feel shame?

    Six years have passed since the Amitabha Assembly began. Heaven blesses the lord's vigor and strength, surely to his great age. To revere the scriptures is to see the ocean of the Three Teachings within the heart's measure; to hold the Buddha in mind is to find the bliss of the Nine Grades within a single step. Thus old transgressions fade, new blessings grow, and their benefit flows to all creatures. How could one doubt this?

    Only this remains uncertain: whether those who come after him as benefactors of this temple will preserve his spirit for a hundred generations and more, or whether their dedication will fade. Ah, this very uncertainty is why he sought this record.

    The lord served as minister to the late king, towering foremost in virtue. Even now, court and country look to him as to Mount Tai—steadfast, immovable. His heart prays ever for blessings on the throne, and in this shared benefit to both realm and self, his devotion has not wavered with the passing years. Is this not a beacon for all who come after?

    Minister Lim of the Left, Jungchangbu, came bearing the lord's request for these words, saying: "This is something the historian should record." So I do not decline, but set down this record.
  footnotes:
    - The cyclical years mentioned (Kyemi, Muja, etc.) follow the traditional sexagenary cycle of Classical Chinese timekeeping, roughly corresponding to the 14th-15th centuries.
    - The 'Great Scripture Collection' (Daejangjing) refers to the complete Buddhist canon, a monumental work requiring significant resources to produce and maintain.
    - The Nine Grades (Guipum) refer to levels of rebirth in the Pure Land according to Pure Land Buddhism.
    - White Horse Mountain (Baekmaasan) and the locations mentioned (Buphyeong, Gimpo, etc.) are historical sites in the Korean peninsula.
